The article discusses the need for reform and acceleration of the Superfund program, which deals with the cleanup of toxic waste sites. The author criticizes the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) for prioritizing climate change over more immediate environmental problems. EPA Administrator Scott Pruitt plans to address this issue by reforming the Superfund program and expediting the cleanup of hazardous waste sites. The article highlights the slow pace and bureaucratic obstacles that have hindered the progress of Superfund cleanup. The author argues that success should be measured by the number of sites cleaned up, rather than the amount of money spent. By focusing on Superfund cleanup, Pruitt could make a significant contribution to the environment.